                 {
                  "type": "tool_result",
                  "tool_use_id": "toolu_01JBJjHSdWULADKab3o9MXC2",
                  "content": "\n        1:\ufeff\"\"\"Development decorators for enhancing bot functionality and debugging.\n        2:\n        3:This module provides decorators and utilities for:\n        4:- Lazy implementation using LLMs (@lazy)\n        5:- Lazy function implementation using LLMs (@lazy_fn)\n        6:- Lazy class implementation using LLMs (@lazy_class)\n        7:- Post-mortem debugging on exceptions (@debug_on_error)\n        8:- Error logging to file (@log_errors)\n        9:- HTTP logging filters for cleaner output\n        10:\n        11:The primary features are:\n        12:- @lazy_impl: Smart decorator that chooses between lazy and lazy_class based on the type\n        13:- @lazy: Generates function implementations at runtime using LLM\n        14:- @lazy_class: Generates class implementations at runtime using LLM\n        15:- @debug_on_error: Launches pdb debugger on exceptions\n        16:- @log_errors: Logs exceptions and error messages to a file\n        17:    from bots.dev.decorators import lazy_impl, lazy, lazy_class, debug_on_error, log_errors\n        18:\n        19:Example:\n        20:    from bots.dev.decorators import lazy_impl, lazy, lazy_class, debug_on_error\n        21:\n        22:    # Smart decorator that works with both functions and classes\n        23:    @lazy(\"Implement a quicksort algorithm\")\n        24:    def sort_list(items: list) -> list:\n        25:        pass  # Implementation will be generated by LLM\n        26:\n        27:    @lazy(\"Implement a persistent key-value store with TTL\")\n        28:    class KeyValueStore:\n        29:        pass  # Implementation will be generated by LLM\n        30:\n        31:    # Also can use specific decorators\n        32:    @lazy_fn(\"Implement a merge sort algorithm\")\n        33:    def merge_sort(items: list) -> list:\n        34:        pass\n        35:\n        36:    @lazy_class(\"Implement a cache with LRU policy\")\n        37:    class LRUCache:\n        38:        pass\n        39:\n        40:    @debug_on_error\n        41:    def risky_operation():\n        42:        # Will launch debugger if this raises an exception\n        43:        process_data()\n        44:\n        45:    @log_errors\n        46:    def might_error():\n        47:        # Will log any exceptions or \"Error\" messages to error_log.txt\n        48:        return \"Error: Something went wrong\"\n        49:\"\"\"\n        50:\n        51:import os\n        52:import sys\n        53:import ast\n        54:import inspect\n        55:import logging\n        56:import traceback\n        57:import textwrap\n        58:import datetime\n        59:from functools import wraps\n        60:from typing import Any, Callable, Optional, Type\n        61:from bots.utils.helpers import remove_code_blocks\n        62:from bots.foundation.base import Bot\n        63:from bots import AnthropicBot\n        64:logging.basicConfig(level=logging.WARNING, format='%(asctime)s - %(name)s - %(levelname)s - %(message)s')\n        65:logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n        66:logger.setLevel(logging.DEBUG)\n        67:\n        68:class NoHTTPFilter(logging.Filter):\n        69:    \"\"\"Filters out logging records containing 'response' in the logger name.\n        70:\n        71:    Use when you need to reduce noise from HTTP-related logging in the application.\n        72:    This filter helps prevent logging output from being flooded with HTTP response\n        73:    logs while still maintaining other important log messages.\n        74:\n        75:    Inherits from:\n        76:        logging.Filter: Base class for logging filters\n        77:\n        78:    Attributes:\n        79:        name (str): The name of the filter (inherited from logging.Filter)\n        80:\n        81:    Example:\n        82:        logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n        83:        http_filter = NoHTTPFilter()\n        84:        logger.addFilter(http_filter)\n        85:    \"\"\"\n        86:\n        87:    def filter(self, record: logging.LogRecord) -> bool:\n        88:        \"\"\"Check if the log record should be filtered.\n        89:\n        90:        Parameters:\n        91:            record (logging.LogRecord): The log record to be checked\n        92:\n        93:        Returns:\n        94:            bool: True if the record should be kept (doesn't contain 'response'),\n        95:                 False if it should be filtered out\n        96:        \"\"\"\n        97:        return 'response' not in record.name.lower()\n        98:\n        99:logger.addFilter(NoHTTPFilter())\n        100:\n        101:def lazy_fn(prompt: Optional[str]=None, bot: Optional[Bot]=None, context: Optional[str]=None) -> Callable:\n        102:    \"\"\"Decorator that lazily implements a function using an LLM at runtime.\n        103:\n        104:    Use when you need to generate function implementations dynamically using an LLM.\n        105:    The implementation will be generated on first call and persisted to the source file.\n        106:\n        107:    Parameters:\n        108:        prompt (Optional[str]): Additional instructions for the LLM about how to implement\n        109:            the function. Defaults to empty string.\n        110:        bot (Optional[Bot]): The bot instance to use for implementation. Defaults to\n        111:            a new AnthropicBot instance.\n        112:        context (Optional[str]): Level of context to provide to the LLM. Options are:\n        113:            - 'None': No additional context\n        114:            - 'low': Only the containing class\n        115:            - 'medium': The entire current file\n        116:            - 'high': Current file and interfaces of other files in directory\n        117:            - 'very high': All Python files in directory\n        118:            Defaults to 'None'.\n        119:\n        120:    Returns:\n        121:        Callable: A decorator function that wraps the target function\n        122:\n        123:    Example:\n        124:        @lazy(\"Sort using a funny algorithm. Name variables as though you're a clown.\")\n        125:        def sort(arr: list[int]) -> list[int]:\n        126:            pass\n        127:    \"\"\"\n        128:\n        129:    def decorator(func: Callable) -> Callable:\n        130:        \"\"\"Inner decorator function that sets up the lazy implementation.\n        131:\n        132:        This decorator initializes the lazy implementation environment by:\n        133:        1. Setting up default bot if none provided\n        134:        2. Setting up default prompt if none provided\n        135:        3. Setting up default context level if none provided\n        136:\n        137:        Parameters:\n        138:            func (Callable): The function to be lazily implemented\n        139:\n        140:        Returns:\n        141:            Callable: A wrapped version of the function that will be implemented on first call\n        142:\n        143:        Note:\n        144:            The actual implementation is generated in the wrapper function on first call.\n        145:        \"\"\"\n        146:        nonlocal bot, prompt, context\n        147:        if bot is None:\n        148:            bot = AnthropicBot(name='Claude')\n        149:        if prompt is None:\n        150:            prompt = ''\n        151:        if context is None:\n        152:            context = 'None'\n        153:\n        154:        def wrapper(*args: Any, **kwargs: Any) -> Any:\n        155:            \"\"\"Wrapper function that handles lazy function implementation.\n        156:\n        157:            This wrapper checks if the function has been implemented. If not, it:\n        158:            1. Gets appropriate context based on context_level\n        159:            2. Generates implementation using the LLM\n        160:            3. Updates the source file with the new implementation\n        161:            4. Executes the new implementation\n        162:\n        163:            Parameters:\n        164:                *args (Any): Positional arguments to pass to the implemented function\n        165:                **kwargs (Any): Keyword arguments to pass to the implemented function\n        166:\n        167:            Returns:\n        168:                Any: The result of the implemented function\n        169:            \"\"\"\n        170:            nonlocal func\n        171:            if not hasattr(wrapper, 'initialized') or not wrapper.initialized:\n        172:                function_name: str = func.__name__\n        173:                logger.debug(f'Initializing lazy function: {function_name}')\n        174:                context_content = _get_context(func, context)\n        175:                instructions: str = textwrap.dedent(\n        176:                    \"\"\"Please fill out the following\n        177:                    function definition according to the following requirements.\n        178:                    Respond only with the code in a single code block. Include all\n        179:                    import statements inside the function definition. Remove the lazy\n        180:                    decorator. Respond only with the function definition, including\n        181:                    any new decorators and docstring. Include 'gen by @lazy' in the\n        182:                    docstring. Use PEP8 convention with type hints for all variables.\"\"\"\n        183:                    )\n        184:                complete_prompt: str = textwrap.dedent(\n        185:                    f\"\"\"\n        186:                    {instructions}\n        187:\n        188:                    {prompt}\n        189:\n        190:                    {context_content}\n        191:\n        192:                    {function_name}{str(inspect.signature(func))}\"\"\"\n        193:                    )\n        194:                response: str = bot.respond(complete_prompt)\n        195:                function_code, _ = remove_code_blocks(response)\n        196:                function_code = function_code[0]\n        197:                logger.debug(f'Generated function code:\\n{function_code}')\n        198:                source_file: str = inspect.getfile(func)\n        199:                logger.debug(f'Source file: {source_file}')\n        200:                with open(source_file, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as file:\n        201:                    source_lines: str = file.read()\n        202:                logger.debug(f'Original source file content:\\n{source_lines}')\n        203:                source_tree: ast.AST = ast.parse(source_lines)\n        204:\n        205:                class FunctionReplacer(ast.NodeTransformer):\n        206:                    \"\"\"AST transformer that replaces a function definition with new code.\n        207:\n        208:                    This transformer walks the AST and replaces a specific function's\n        209:                    definition with new code while preserving the rest of the module.\n        210:\n        211:                    Attributes:\n        212:                        function_name (str): Name of the function to be replaced\n        213:                        new_code (str): New implementation code to replace the function with\n        214:                    \"\"\"\n        215:\n        216:                    def __init__(self, function_name: str, new_code: str):\n        217:                        self.function_name = function_name\n        218:                        self.new_code = new_code\n        219:\n        220:                    def visit_FunctionDef(self, node: ast.FunctionDef) -> ast.AST:\n        221:                        if node.name == self.function_name:\n        222:                            logger.debug(f'Replacing function: {self.function_name}')\n        223:                            new_node: ast.AST = ast.parse(self.new_code).body[0]\n        224:                            return new_node\n        225:                        return node\n        226:                function_replacer = FunctionReplacer(function_name, function_code)\n        227:                new_tree: ast.AST = function_replacer.visit(source_tree)\n        228:                ast.fix_missing_locations(new_tree)\n        229:                new_source_lines: str = ast.unparse(new_tree)\n        230:                logger.debug(f'New source file content:\\n{new_source_lines}')\n        231:                with open(source_file, 'w', encoding='utf-8') as file:\n        232:                    file.write(new_source_lines)\n        233:                logger.debug('Updated source file written')\n        234:                exec(function_code, globals())\n        235:                func = globals()[function_name]\n        236:                wrapper.initialized = True\n        237:                logger.debug(f'Lazy function {function_name} initialized')\n        238:            return func(*args, **kwargs)\n        239:        wrapper.initialized = False\n        240:        return wrapper\n        241:    return decorator\n        242:\n        243:def lazy_class(prompt: Optional[str]=None, bot: Optional[Bot]=None, context: Optional[str]=None) -> Callable:\n        244:    \"\"\"Decorator that lazily implements a class using an LLM at runtime.\n        245:\n        246:    Use when you need to generate class implementations dynamically using an LLM.\n        247:    The implementation will be generated on first instantiation and persisted to the source file.\n        248:\n        249:    Parameters:\n        250:        prompt (Optional[str]): Additional instructions for the LLM about how to implement\n        251:            the class. Defaults to empty string.\n        252:        bot (Optional[Bot]): The bot instance to use for implementation. Defaults to\n        253:            a new AnthropicBot instance.\n        254:        context (Optional[str]): Level of context to provide to the LLM. Options are:\n        255:            - 'None': No additional context\n        256:            - 'low': Only the containing module's imports and global variables\n        257:            - 'medium': The entire current file\n        258:            - 'high': Current file and interfaces of other files in directory\n        259:            - 'very high': All Python files in directory\n        260:            Defaults to 'None'.\n        261:\n        262:    Returns:\n        263:        Callable: A decorator function that wraps the target class\n        264:\n        265:    Example:\n        266:        @lazy_class(\"Implement a key-value store with Redis-like functionality\")\n        267:        class DataStore:\n        268:            pass  # Will be implemented by LLM\n        269:    \"\"\"\n        270:\n        271:    def decorator(cls: Type) -> Type:\n        272:        \"\"\"Inner decorator function that sets up the lazy class implementation.\n        273:\n        274:        Parameters:\n        275:            cls (Type): The class to be lazily implemented\n        276:\n        277:        Returns:\n        278:            Type: A wrapped version of the class that will be implemented on first instantiation\n        279:        \"\"\"\n        280:        nonlocal bot, prompt, context\n        281:        if bot is None:\n        282:            bot = AnthropicBot(name='Claude')\n        283:        if prompt is None:\n        284:            prompt = ''\n        285:        if context is None:\n        286:            context = 'None'\n        287:\n        288:        # Store the original __new__ method\n        289:        original_new = cls.__new__\n        290:\n        291:        @wraps(original_new)\n        292:        def new_new(cls_self, *args, **kwargs):\n        293:            \"\"\"Replacement for __new__ that handles lazy class implementation.\n        294:\n        295:            This method checks if the class has been implemented. If not, it:\n        296:            1. Gets appropriate context based on context_level\n        297:            2. Generates implementation using the LLM\n        298:            3. Updates the source file with the new implementation\n        299:            4. Recreates the class with the new implementation\n        300:\n        301:            Parameters:\n        302:                cls_self (Type): The class being instantiated\n        303:                *args (Any): Positional arguments to pass to the original __new__\n        304:                **kwargs (Any): Keyword arguments to pass to the original __new__\n        305:\n        306:            Returns:\n        307:                Any: A new instance of the implemented class\n        308:            \"\"\"\n        309:            if not hasattr(cls, '_lazy_initialized') or not cls._lazy_initialized:\n        310:                class_name: str = cls.__name__\n        311:                logger.debug(f'Initializing lazy class: {class_name}')\n        312:\n        313:                # Get context for the class\n        314:                context_content = _get_context(cls, context)\n        315:\n        316:                # Create prompt for LLM\n        317:                instructions: str = textwrap.dedent(\n        318:                    \"\"\"Please implement the following class according to these requirements.\n        319:                    Respond only with the code in a single code block. Include all\n        320:                    import statements inside the class definition. Remove the lazy_class\n        321:                    decorator. Respond only with the class definition, including\n        322:                    any new decorators and docstring. Include 'gen by @lazy' in the\n        323:                    docstring. Use PEP8 convention with type hints.\"\"\"\n        324:                    )\n        325:\n        326:                # Get the original class source code\n        327:                try:\n        328:                    original_class_code = inspect.getsource(cls)\n        329:                except (TypeError, OSError):\n        330:                    # Fall back to a basic class definition if source can't be retrieved\n        331:                    original_class_code = f\"class {class_name}:\\n    pass\"\n        332:\n        333:                complete_prompt: str = textwrap.dedent(\n        334:                    f\"\"\"\n        335:                    {instructions}\n        336:\n        337:                    {prompt}\n        338:\n        339:                    {context_content}\n        340:\n        341:                    {original_class_code}\"\"\"\n        342:                    )\n        343:\n        344:                # Get implementation from LLM\n        345:                response: str = bot.respond(complete_prompt)\n        346:                class_code, _ = remove_code_blocks(response)\n        347:                class_code = class_code[0]\n        348:                logger.debug(f'Generated class code:\\n{class_code}')\n        349:\n        350:                # Update source file with new implementation\n        351:                source_file: str = inspect.getfile(cls)\n        352:                logger.debug(f'Source file: {source_file}')\n        353:\n        354:                with open(source_file, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as file:\n        355:                    source_lines: str = file.read()\n        356:                logger.debug(f'Original source file content:\\n{source_lines}')\n        357:\n        358:                source_tree: ast.AST = ast.parse(source_lines)\n        359:\n        360:                class ClassReplacer(ast.NodeTransformer):\n        361:                    \"\"\"AST transformer that replaces a class definition with new code.\n        362:\n        363:                    This transformer walks the AST and replaces a specific class's\n        364:                    definition with new code while preserving the rest of the module.\n        365:\n        366:                    Attributes:\n        367:                        class_name (str): Name of the class to be replaced\n        368:                        new_code (str): New implementation code to replace the class with\n        369:                    \"\"\"\n        370:\n        371:                    def __init__(self, class_name: str, new_code: str):\n        372:                        self.class_name = class_name\n        373:                        self.new_code = new_code\n        374:\n        375:                    def visit_ClassDef(self, node: ast.ClassDef) -> ast.AST:\n        376:                        if node.name == self.class_name:\n        377:                            logger.debug(f'Replacing class: {self.class_name}')\n        378:                            new_node: ast.AST = ast.parse(self.new_code).body[0]\n        379:                            return new_node\n        380:                        return node\n        381:\n        382:                class_replacer = ClassReplacer(class_name, class_code)\n        383:                new_tree: ast.AST = class_replacer.visit(source_tree)\n        384:                ast.fix_missing_locations(new_tree)\n        385:\n        386:                new_source_lines: str = ast.unparse(new_tree)\n        387:                logger.debug(f'New source file content:\\n{new_source_lines}')\n        388:\n        389:                with open(source_file, 'w', encoding='utf-8') as file:\n        390:                    file.write(new_source_lines)\n        391:                logger.debug('Updated source file written')\n        392:\n        393:                # Execute the