                                                                    "replies": [
                                                                     {
                                                                      "content": "Perfect! I've successfully added the `@handle_errors` decorator to your `bots/dev/decorators.py` file. Here's what was added:\n\n## New Decorator: `@handle_errors`\n\nThe decorator does exactly what you wanted - it wraps functions in a try-except block and returns formatted error strings instead of raising exceptions.\n\n**Usage:**\n```python\n@handle_errors\ndef risky_operation(data):\n    # Your code here\n    return process_data(data)\n\n# Instead of raising an exception, it returns an error string\nresult = risky_operation(bad_data)\nif result.startswith(\"Tool Failed:\"):\n    print(f\"Operation failed: {result}\")\n```\n\n**What it does:**\n- Catches any exception that occurs in the decorated function\n- Uses your existing `_process_error()` helper function to format the error\n- Returns the formatted error string instead of raising the exception\n- Preserves the original function's signature and metadata using `@wraps`\n\n**Key features:**\n- Uses your existing `_process_error` function for consistent error formatting\n- Includes full tracebacks in the error messages\n- Perfect for tools and APIs that need graceful error handling\n- Simple to apply - just add `@handle_errors` above any function definition\n\nThe import for `_process_error` was also automatically added to the imports section of the decorators file.",
                                                                      "pending_results": [],
                                                                      "role": "assistant",
                                                                      "tool_calls": [],
