                                                                                                                                                                                                                      "content": "Perfect! The `@handle_errors` decorator is working correctly. It's catching the ValueError and returning it as a formatted error string with \"Tool Failed:\" and the traceback, just like the original `_process_error` function would have done.\n\n## Summary\n\nI have successfully updated `python_edit.py` (item 3 in the tools list) to use the `@handle_errors` decorator instead of manual try-catch blocks. Here's what was accomplished:\n\n1. **Replaced the decorator**: Changed from `@log_errors` to `@handle_errors`\n2. **Updated the import**: Changed from `log_errors` to `handle_errors` \n3. **Preserved functionality**: The function still handles errors properly, returning formatted error messages instead of raising exceptions\n4. **Maintained compatibility**: All existing tests pass, confirming that the behavior is preserved\n\nThe `@handle_errors` decorator automatically wraps the function in a try-catch block and uses `_process_error()` to format any exceptions into user-friendly error strings, eliminating the need for manual error handling code within the function.\n\nThe tests confirm that:\n- Basic functionality works (file editing, class replacement, imports, etc.)\n- Error handling works correctly (invalid file extensions, parsing errors, etc.)\n- The decorator properly catches exceptions and returns formatted error messages\n\nThis approach is much cleaner than the previous manual try-catch blocks and provides consistent error handling across the codebase.",
